    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-11-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-11-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="638"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d638">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">103.96/1607: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-11-30">November 30,
                            1918</date>.<lb/>[Received November 30—4:46 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4185. War Trade Board [from Sheldon]: No. 1970. To Woolley and Gay from
                        Peterson.<note n="21" xml:id="d638fn21">Fred B. Peterson, director of the
                        Bureau of Imports of the War Trade Board.</note> Finally succeeded in seeing
                    Sir Albert Stanley, President of Board of Trade. Had no trouble in arranging
                    with him for reciprocal exchange of information concerning relaxation of import
                    restrictions as nearly as possible. One week’s notice is to be given by each to
                    the other before public announcement is made, meanwhile such information to be
                    kept confidential for governmental use. Only channel of transmission to be
                    through Sheldon and Fontaine of Board of Trade. This becoming effective
                    forthwith Board of Trade now appears most anxious for full cooperation with us
                    in all matters affecting supplies of raw material, and is convinced of the
                    necessity of control through licensing system for an indefinite period. Leave
                    today for Paris.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
